Subject: existence starts at point [RO:0002583]

Subject: existence ends at point [RO:0002593]
Value: x existence starts at point y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: directly activates [RO:0002406]
Value: p directly activates q if and only if p is immediately upstream of q and p is the realization of a function to increase the rate or activity of q

Subject: indirectly activates [RO:0002407]
Value: p directly activates q if and only if p is immediately upstream of q and p is the realization of a function to increase the rate or activity of q

Subject: lays eggs on [RO:0008507]
Value: An interaction relationship in which organism a lays eggs on the outside surface of organism b. Organism b is neither helped nor harmed in the process of egg laying or incubation.

Subject: has eggs laid on by [RO:0008508]
Value: An interaction relationship in which organism a lays eggs on the outside surface of organism b. Organism b is neither helped nor harmed in the process of egg laying or incubation.

Subject: upstream in neural circuit with [RO:0000301]
Value: A relation that holds between a neuron that is synapsed_to another neuron or a neuron that is connected indirectly to another by a chain of neurons, each synapsed_to the next.@en

Subject: downstream in neural circuit with [RO:0000302]
Value: A relation that holds between a neuron that is synapsed_to another neuron or a neuron that is connected indirectly to another by a chain of neurons, each synapsed_to the next.@en

Subject: in neural circuit with [RO:0000300]
Value: (forall (?x ?y)         (iff             (neural_circuit_path  ?x ?y)            (and                (\"neuron ; CL_0000540\" ?x)                (\"neuron ; CL_0000540\" ?y)                (or                     (synapsed_by ?x ?y)                     (synapsed_to ?x ?y)))))         (forall (...s ?x ?y ?z)         (iff             (neural_circuit_path  ...s ?x ?y ?z)            (and                (neural_circuit_path  ...s ?x ?y)                (\"neuron ; CL_0000540\" ?z)                (or                     (synapsed_by ?y ?z)                     (synapsed_to ?y ?z)))))         (forall (?x ?y)         (iff             (in_neural_circuit_with ?x ?y)            (exists (...s)                (neural_circuit_path  ?x ...s ?y))))

Value: There are two ways to encode this as a shortcut relation. The other possibility to use an annotation assertion between two classes, and expand this to a disjointness axiom. @en

Subject: capable of [RO:0002215]
Value: A relation between a material entity (such as a cell) and a process, in which the material entity has the ability to carry out the process.

Subject: developmentally induced by [RO:0002256]
Value: Developmental Biology, Gilbert, 8th edition, figure 6.5(F)

Subject: results in maturation of [RO:0002299]
Value: an annotation of gene X to cell maturation with results_in_maturation_of CL:0000057 (fibroblast) means that the fibroblast is mature at the end of the process

Subject: contributes to [RO:0002326]
Value: In the context of the Gene Ontology, contributes_to may be used only with classes from the molecular function ontology.

Subject: results in transport along [RO:0002341]
Value: Holds between p and l when p is a transportation or localization process and the outcome of this process is to move c from one location to another, and the route taken by c follows a path that is aligned_with l

Subject: results in specification of [RO:0002356]
Value: The relationship linking a cell and its participation in a process that results in the fate of the cell being specified. Once specification has taken place, a cell will be committed to differentiate down a specific pathway if left in its normal environment.

Subject: obsolete has direct output [RO:0002402]
Value: p has direct input c iff c is a participanti n p, c is present at the end of p, and c is not present at the beginning of c.

Subject: always present in taxon [RO:0002504]
Value: This is a very strong relation. Often we will not have enough evidence to know for sure that there are no species within a lineage that lack the structure - loss is common in evolution. However, there are some statements we can make with confidence - no vertebrate lineage could persist without a brain or a heart. All primates are limbed.

Subject: sequentially related to [RO:0002514]
Value: A relation that holds between two entities that have the property of being sequences or having sequences.

Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a specifically dependent continuant (the dependent), in which the dependent specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Value: a relation between a continuant and a process, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: has participant [RO:0000057]
Value: a relation between a process and a continuant, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: function of [RO:0000079]
Value: a relation between a function and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: quality of [RO:0000080]
Value: a relation between a quality and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: derives from [RO:0001000]
Value: a relation between two distinct material entities, the new entity and the old entity, in which the new entity begins to exist when the old entity ceases to exist, and the new entity inherits the significant portion of the matter of the old entity@en

Subject: derives into [RO:0001001]
Value: a relation between two distinct material entities, the old entity and the new entity, in which the new entity begins to exist when the old entity ceases to exist, and the new entity inherits the significant portion of the matter of the old entity@en

Subject: location of [RO:0001015]
Value: a relation between two independent continuants, the location and the target, in which the target is entirely within the location@en

Subject: located in [RO:0001025]
Value: a relation between two independent continuants, the target and the location, in which the target is entirely within the location@en

Subject: axiom holds for all times [RO:0001901]
Value: ## Elucidation        This is used when the statement/axiom is assumed to hold true 'eternally'        ## How to interpret (informal)        First the \"atemporal\" FOL is derived from the OWL using the standard    interpretation. This axiom is temporalized by embedding the axiom    within a for-all-times quantified sentence. The t argument is added to    all instantiation predicates and predicates that use this relation.        ## Example            Class: nucleus        SubClassOf: part_of some cell            forall t :          forall n :            instance_of(n,Nucleus,t)             implies            exists c :              instance_of(c,Cell,t)              part_of(n,c,t)        ## Notes        This interpretation is *not* the same as an at-all-times relation

Subject: relation has no temporal argument [RO:0001902]
Value: ## Elucidation        This is used when the first-order logic form of the relation is    binary, and takes no temporal argument.        ## Example:            Class: limb        SubClassOf: develops_from some lateral-plate-mesoderm             forall t, t2:          forall x :            instance_of(x,Limb,t)             implies            exists y :              instance_of(y,LPM,t2)              develops_from(x,y)

Subject: 2D boundary of [RO:0002000]
Value: a relation between a 2D immaterial entity (the boundary) and a material entity, in which the boundary delimits the material entity@en

Subject: has 2D boundary [RO:0002002]
Value: a relation between a material entity and a 2D immaterial entity (the boundary), in which the boundary delimits the material entity@en

Subject: regulates in other organism [RO:0002010]
Value: x 'regulates in other organism' y if and only if: (x is the realization of a function to exert an effect on the frequency, rate or extent of y) AND (the agents of x are produced by organism o1 and the agents of y are produced by organism o2).

Subject: has component process [RO:0002018]
Value: w 'has process component' p if p and w are processes,  w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: fasciculates with [RO:0002101]
Value: relationship between a neuron and a neuron projection bundle (e.g.- tract or nerve bundle) that one or more of its projections travels through.    @en

Subject: synapsed to [RO:0002120]
Value: Relation between a neuron and an anatomical structure (including cells) that it chemically synapses to.            @en

Subject: overlaps [RO:0002131]
Value: x overlaps y if and only if there exists some z such that x has part z and z part of y

Subject: partially overlaps [RO:0002151]
Value: x partially overlaps y iff there exists some z such that z is part of x and z is part of y, and it is also the case that neither x is part of y or y is part of x

Subject: derived by descent from [RO:0002156]
Value: d derived_by_descent_from a if d is specified by some genetic program that is sequence-inherited-from a genetic program that specifies a.

Subject: has derived by descendant [RO:0002157]
Value: inverse of derived by descent from

Subject: shares ancestor with [RO:0002158]
Value: two individual entities d1 and d2 stand in a shares_ancestor_with relation if and only if there exists some a such that d1 derived_by_descent_from a and d2 derived_by_descent_from a.

Subject: only in taxon [RO:0002160]
Value: x only in taxon y if and only if x is in taxon y, and there is no other organism z such that y!=z a and x is in taxon z.

Subject: never in taxon [RO:0002161]
Value: x never in taxon T if and only if T is a class, and x does not instantiate the class expression \"in taxon some T\". Note that this is a shortcut relation, and should be used as a hasValue restriction in OWL.

Subject: in taxon [RO:0002162]
Value: x is in taxon y if an only if y is an organism, and the relationship between x and y is one of: part of (reflexive), developmentally preceded by, derives from, secreted by, expressed.

Subject: connected to [RO:0002170]
Value: a is connected to b if and only if a and b are discrete structure, and there exists some connecting structure c, such that c connects a and b

Subject: connects [RO:0002176]
Value: c connects a if and only if there exist some b such that a and b are similar parts of the same system, and c connects b, specifically, c connects a with b. When one structure connects two others it unites some aspect of the function or role they play within the system.

Subject: attached to part of [RO:0002177]
Value: a is attached to part of b if a is attached to b, or a is attached to some p, where p is part of b.

Subject: has component [RO:0002180]
Value: w 'has component' p if w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: phenotype of [RO:0002201]
Value: inverse of has phenotype

Subject: develops from [RO:0002202]
Value: x develops from y if and only if either (a) x directly develops from y or (b) there exists some z such that x directly develops from z and z develops from y

Subject: develops into [RO:0002203]
Value: inverse of develops from

Subject: gene product of [RO:0002204]
Value: definition \"x has gene product of y if and only if y is a gene (SO:0000704) that participates in some gene expression process (GO:0010467) where the output of that process is either y or something that is ribosomally translated from x\"

Subject: has gene product [RO:0002205]
Value: x has gene product y if and only if x is a gene (SO:0000704) that participates in some gene expression process (GO:0010467) where the output of that process is either y or something that is ribosomally translated from y

Subject: expressed in [RO:0002206]
Value: x expressed in y if and only if there is a gene expression process (GO:0010467) that occurs in y, and one of the following holds: (i) x is a gene, and x is transcribed into a transcript as part of the gene expression process (ii) x is a transcript, and the transcription of x is part of the gene expression process (iii) x is a mature gene product such as a protein, and x was translated or otherwise processes from a transcript that was transcribed as part of this gene expression process

Subject: has parasitoid [RO:0002209]
Value: inverse of parasitoid of

Subject: directly develops into [RO:0002210]
Value: inverse of directly develops from

Subject: regulates [RO:0002211]
Value: process(P1) regulates process(P2) iff: P1 results in the initiation or termination of P2 OR affects the frequency of its initiation or termination OR affects the magnitude or rate of output of P2.

Subject: has prototype [RO:0002214]
Value: x has prototype y if and only if x is an instance of C and y is a prototypical instance of C. For example, every instance of heart, both normal and abnormal is related by the has prototype relation to some instance of a \"canonical\" heart, which participates in blood circulation.

Subject: capable of part of [RO:0002216]
Value: c stands in this relationship to p if and only if there exists some p' such that c is capable_of p', and p' is part_of p.

Subject: actively participates in [RO:0002217]
Value: x actively participates in y if and only if x participates in y and x realizes some active role

Subject: obsolete has active participant [RO:0002218]
Value: x has participant y if and only if x realizes some active role that inheres in y

Subject: surrounded by [RO:0002219]
Value: x surrounded_by y if and only if (1) x is adjacent to y and for every region r that is adjacent to x, r overlaps y (2) the shared boundary between x and y occupies the majority of the outermost boundary of x

Subject: adjacent to [RO:0002220]
Value: x adjacent to y if and only if x and y share a boundary.

Subject: surrounds [RO:0002221]
Value: inverse of surrounded by

Subject: starts [RO:0002223]
Value: inverse of starts with

Subject: starts with [RO:0002224]
Value: x starts with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: α(y) = α(x) ∧ ω(y) < ω(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.

Subject: develops from part of [RO:0002225]
Value: x develops from part of y if and only if there exists some z such that x develops from z and z is part of y

Subject: develops in [RO:0002226]
Value: x develops_in y if x is located in y whilst x is developing

Subject: ends [RO:0002229]
Value: inverse of ends with

Subject: ends with [RO:0002230]
Value: x ends with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: α(y) > α(x) ∧ ω(y) = ω(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.

Subject: has start location [RO:0002231]
Value: x 'has starts location' y if and only if there exists some process z such that x 'starts with' z and z 'occurs in' y

Subject: has end location [RO:0002232]
Value: x 'has end location' y if and only if there exists some process z such that x 'ends with' z and z 'occurs in' y

Subject: has input [RO:0002233]
Value: p has input c iff: p is a process, c is a material entity, c is a participant in p, c is present at the start of p, and the state of c is modified during p.

Subject: has output [RO:0002234]
Value: p has output c iff c is a participant in p, c is present at the end of p, and c is not present at the beginning of p.

Subject: over-expressed in [RO:0002245]
Value: g is over-expressed in t iff g is expressed in t, and the expression level of g is increased relative to some background.

Subject: under-expressed in [RO:0002246]
Value: g is under-expressed in t iff g is expressed in t, and the expression level of g is decreased relative to some background.

Subject: active ingredient in\' [RO:0002249]
Value: inverse of has active ingredient

Subject: connecting branch of [RO:0002252]
Value: b connecting-branch-of s iff b is connected to s, and there exists some tree-like structure t such that the mereological sum of b plus s is either the same as t or a branching-part-of t.

Subject: has connecting branch [RO:0002253]
Value: inverse of connecting branch of

Subject: has developmental contribution from [RO:0002254]
Value: x has developmental contribution from y iff x has some part z such that z develops from y@en

Subject: developmentally contributes to [RO:0002255]
Value: inverse of has developmental contribution from

Subject: developmentally induced by [RO:0002256]
Value: t1 induced_by t2 if there is a process of developmental induction (GO:0031128) with t1 and t2 as interacting participants. t2 causes t1 to change its fate from a precursor anatomical structure type T to T', where T' develops_from T

Subject: has biological role [RO:0002260]
Value: c has-biological-role r iff c has-role r and r is a biological role (CHEBI:24432)

Subject: has application role [RO:0002261]
Value: c has-application-role r iff c has-role r and r is an application role (CHEBI:33232)

Subject: has chemical role [RO:0002262]
Value: c has-chemical-role r iff c has-role r and r is a chemical role (CHEBI:51086)

Subject: acts upstream of [RO:0002263]
Value: c acts upstream of p if and only if c enables some f that is involved in p' and p' occurs chronologically before p, is not part of p, and affects the execution of p. c is a material entity and f, p, p' are processes.

Subject: acts upstream of or within [RO:0002264]
Value: c acts upstream of or within p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of or within p. c is a material entity and p is an process.

Subject: developmentally replaces [RO:0002285]
Value: x developmentally replaces y if and only if there is some developmental process that causes x to move or to cease to exist, and for the site that was occupied by x to become occupied by y, where y either comes into existence in this site or moves to this site from somewhere else

Subject: ubiquitously expressed in [RO:0002291]
Value: x is ubiquitously expressed in y if and only if x is expressed in y, and the majority of cells in y express x

Subject: ubiquitously expresses [RO:0002293]
Value: inverse of ubiquiotously expressed in

Subject: results in developmental progression of [RO:0002295]
Value: p results in the developmental progression of s iff p is a developmental process and s is an anatomical structure and p causes s to undergo a change in state at some point along its natural developmental cycle (this cycle starts with its formation, through the mature structure, and ends with its loss).

Subject: results in development of [RO:0002296]
Value: p 'results in development of' c if and only if p is a developmental process and p results in the state of c changing from its initial state as a primordium or anlage through its mature state and to its final state.

Subject: has habitat [RO:0002303]
Value: x 'has habitat' y if and only if: x is an organism, y is a habitat, and y can sustain and allow the growth of a population of xs.

Subject: inheres in part of [RO:0002314]
Value: q inheres in part of w if and only if there exists some p such that q inheres in p and p part of w.

Subject: colocalizes with [RO:0002325]
Value: a colocalizes_with b if and only if  a is transiently or peripherally associated with b[GO].

Subject: part of structure that is capable of [RO:0002329]
Value: this relation holds between c and p when c is part of some c', and c' is capable of p.

Subject: genomically related to [RO:0002330]
Value: holds between two entities when some genome-level process such as gene expression is involved. This includes transcriptional, spliceosomal events. These relations can be used between either macromolecule entities (such as regions of nucleic acid) or between their abstract informational counterparts.

Subject: involved in [RO:0002331]
Value: c involved_in p if and only if c enables some process p', and p' is part of p

Subject: regulates levels of [RO:0002332]
Value: p regulates levels of c if p regulates some amount (PATO:0000070) of c

Subject: enabled by [RO:0002333]
Value: inverse of enables

Subject: regulated by [RO:0002334]
Value: inverse of regulates

Subject: negatively regulated by [RO:0002335]
Value: inverse of negatively regulates

Subject: positively regulated by [RO:0002336]
Value: inverse of positively regulates

Subject: results in commitment to [RO:0002348]
Value: p 'results in commitment to' c if and only if p is a developmental process and c is a cell and p results in the state of c changing such that is can only develop into a single cell type.

Subject: results in determination of [RO:0002349]
Value: p 'results in determination of' c if and only if p is a developmental process and c is a cell and p results in the state of c changing to be determined. Once a cell becomes determined, it becomes committed to differentiate down a particular pathway regardless of its environment.

Subject: member of [RO:0002350]
Value: is member of is a mereological relation between a item and a collection.

Subject: has member [RO:0002351]
Value: has member is a mereological relation between a collection and an item.

Subject: input of [RO:0002352]
Value: inverse of has input

Subject: output of [RO:0002353]
Value: inverse of has output

Subject: results in developmental induction of [RO:0002357]
Value: p results in developmental induction of c if and only if p is a collection of cell-cell signaling processes that signal to a neighbouring tissue that is the precursor of the mature c, where the signaling results in the commitment to cell types necessary for the formation of c.

Subject: attached to [RO:0002371]
Value: a is attached to b if and only if a and b are discrete objects or object parts, and there are physical connections between a and b such that a force pulling a will move b, or a force pulling b will move a

Subject: has muscle origin [RO:0002372]
Value: m has_muscle_origin s iff m is attached_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s does not move. The site of the origin tends to be more proximal and have greater mass than what the other end attaches to.@en

Subject: has muscle insertion [RO:0002373]
Value: m has_muscle_insertion s iff m is attaches_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s moves. Insertions are usually connections of muscle via tendon to bone.@en

Subject: derived from ancestral fusion of [RO:0002374]
Value: x has_fused_element y iff: there exists some z : x has_part z, z homologous_to y, and y is a distinct element, the boundary between x and z is largely fiat@en

Subject: tributary of [RO:0002376]
Value: x tributary_of y if and only if x a channel for the flow of a substance into y, where y is larger than x. If x and y are hydrographic features, then y is the main stem of a river, or a lake or bay, but not the sea or ocean. If x and y are anatomical, then y is a vein.

Subject: distributary of [RO:0002377]
Value: x distributary_of y if and only if x is capable of channeling the flow of a substance to y, where y channels less of the substance than x

Subject: anabranch of [RO:0002378]
Value: x anabranch_of y if x is a distributary of y (i.e. it channels a from a larger flow from y) and x ultimately channels the flow back into y.

Subject: spatially coextensive with [RO:0002379]
Value: x spatially_coextensive_with y if and inly if x and y have the same location

Subject: branching part of [RO:0002380]
Value: x is a branching part of y if and only if x is part of y and x is connected directly or indirectly to the main stem of y

Subject: main stem of [RO:0002381]
Value: x main_stem_of y if y is a branching structure and x is a channel that traces a linear path through y, such that x has higher capacity than any other such path.

Subject: proper distributary of [RO:0002382]
Value: x proper_distributary_of y iff x distributary_of y and x does not flow back into y

Subject: proper tributary of [RO:0002383]
Value: x proper_tributary_of y iff x tributary_of y and x does not originate from y

Subject: has developmental potential involving [RO:0002384]
Value: x has developmental potential involving y iff x is capable of a developmental process with output y. y may be the successor of x, or may be a different structure in the vicinity (as for example in the case of developmental induction).@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to [RO:0002385]
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally induce [RO:0002386]
Value: x has potential to developmentally induce y iff x developmentally induces y or x is capable of developmentally inducing y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into [RO:0002387]
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to directly develop into [RO:0002388]
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y@en

Subject: has direct input [RO:0002400]
Value: p has direct input c iff c is a participant in p, c is present at the start of p, and the state of c is modified during p.

Subject: obsolete has direct output [RO:0002402]
Value: p has direct input c iff c is a participanti n p, c is present at the end of p, and c is not present at the beginning of c.

Subject: causally downstream of [RO:0002404]
Value: inverse of upstream of

Subject: directly activates [RO:0002406]
Value: p directly activates q if and only if p is immediately upstream of q and p is the realization of a function to increase the rate or activity of q

Subject: indirectly activates [RO:0002407]
Value: p directly activates q if and only if p is immediately upstream of q and p is the realization of a function to increase the rate or activity of q

Subject: causally upstream of [RO:0002411]
Value: p is causally upstream of q if and only if p precedes q and p and q are linked in a causal chain

Subject: immediately causally upstream of [RO:0002412]
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff both (a) p immediately precedes q and (b) p is causally upstream of q. In addition, the output of p  must be an input of q.

Subject: directly provides input for [RO:0002413]
Value: p1 directly provides input for p2 iff there exists some c such that p1 has_output c and p2 has_input c

Subject: transitively provides input for [RO:0002414]
Value: transitive form of directly_provides_input_for

Subject: causally upstream of or within [RO:0002418]
Value: p 'causally upstream or within' q iff (1) the end of p is before the end of q and (2) the execution of p exerts some causal influence over the outputs of q; i.e. if p was abolished or the outputs of p were to be modified, this would necessarily affect q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within [RO:0002427]
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of [RO:0002428]
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of [RO:0002429]
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of [RO:0002430]
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of [RO:0002431]
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: is active in [RO:0002432]
Value: c executes activity in d if and only if c enables p and p occurs_in d.  Assuming no action at a distance by gene products, if a gene product enables (is capable of) a process that occurs in some structure, it must have at least some part in that structure.

Subject: contributes to morphology of [RO:0002433]
Value: p contributes to morphology of w if and only if a change in the morphology of p entails a change in the morphology of w. Examples: every skull contributes to morphology of the head which it is a part of. Counter-example: nuclei do not generally contribute to the morphology of the cell they are part of, as they are buffered by cytoplasm.

Subject: preyed upon by [RO:0002458]
Value: inverse of preys on

Subject: composed primarily of [RO:0002473]
Value: x composed_primarily_of y if and only if more than half of the mass of x is made from y or units of the same type as y.

Subject: child nucleus of [RO:0002476]
Value: c is a child nucleus of d if and only if c and d are both nuclei and parts of cells c' and d', where c' is derived from d' by mitosis and the genetic material in c is a copy of the generic material in d

Subject: has part that occurs in [RO:0002479]
Value: p has part that occurs in c if and only if there exists some p1, such that p has_part p1, and p1 occurs in c.

Subject: existence starts during [RO:0002488]
Value: x existence starts during y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts and before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts during y iff α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y).

Subject: existence starts with [RO:0002489]
Value: x starts ends with y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts with y iff α(x) = α(y).

Subject: existence overlaps [RO:0002490]
Value: x existence overlaps y if and only if either (a) the start of x is part of y or (b) the end of x is part of y. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff (α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y)) OR (ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y))

Subject: existence starts and ends during [RO:0002491]
Value: x existence starts and ends during y if and only if the start of x is part of y and the end of x is part of y. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y)

Subject: existence ends during [RO:0002492]
Value: x existence ends during y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends and after or equivalent to the point at which y starts. Formally: x existence ends during y iff ω(x) <= ω(y) and ω(x) >= α(y).

Subject: existence ends with [RO:0002493]
Value: x existence ends with y if and only if the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence ends with y iff ω(x) = ω(y).

Subject: transformation of [RO:0002494]
Value: x transformation of y if x is the immediate transformation of y, or is linked to y through a chain of transformation relationships

Subject: immediate transformation of [RO:0002495]
Value: x immediate transformation of y iff x immediately succeeds y temporally at a time boundary t, and all of the matter present in x at t is present in y at t, and all the matter in y at t is present in x at t

Subject: existence starts during or after [RO:0002496]
Value: x existence starts during or after y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts during or after y iff α (x) >= α (y).

Subject: existence ends during or before [RO:0002497]
Value: x existence ends during or before y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: causal relation between processes [RO:0002501]
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one of direct activation or direct inhibition. p may be upstream, downstream, part of or a container of q.

Subject: towards [RO:0002503]
Value: q towards e2 if and only if q is a relational quality such that q inheres-in some e, and e != e2 and q is dependent on e2

Subject: has intermediate [RO:0002505]
Value: p has intermediate c if and only if p has parts p1, p2 and p1 has output c, and p2 has input c

Subject: determined by [RO:0002507]
Value: s determined by f if and only if s is a type of system, and f is a material entity that is part of s, such that f exerts a strong causal influence on the functioning of s, and the removal of f would cause the collapse of s.

Subject: determines [RO:0002508]
Value: inverse of determined by

Subject: determined by part of [RO:0002509]
Value: s 'determined by part of' w if and only if there exists some f such that (1) s 'determined by' f and (2) f part_of w, or f=w.

Subject: transcribed from [RO:0002510]
Value: x is transcribed from y if and only if x is synthesized from template y

Subject: transcribed to [RO:0002511]
Value: inverse of transcribed from

Subject: ribosomal translation of [RO:0002512]
Value: x is the ribosomal translation of y if and only if a ribosome reads x through a series of triplet codon-amino acid adaptor activities (GO:0030533) and produces y

Subject: ribosomally translates to [RO:0002513]
Value: inverse of ribosomal translation of

Subject: sequentially adjacent to [RO:0002515]
Value: x is sequentially adjacent to y iff x and y do not overlap and if there are no base units intervening between x and y

Subject: has start sequence [RO:0002516]
Value: x has start sequence y if the start of x is identical to the start of y, and x has y as a subsequence

Subject: is start sequence of [RO:0002517]
Value: inverse of has start sequence

Subject: has end sequence [RO:0002518]
Value: x has end sequence y if the end of x is identical to the end of y, and x has y as a subsequence

Subject: is end sequence of [RO:0002519]
Value: inverse of has end sequence

Subject: is consecutive sequence of [RO:0002520]
Value: x is a consecutive sequence of y iff x has subsequence y, and all the parts of x are made of zero or more repetitions of y or sequences as the same type as y.

Subject: is sequentially aligned with [RO:0002521]
Value: x is sequentially aligned with if a significant portion bases of x and y correspond in terms of their base type and their relative ordering

Subject: bounds sequence of [RO:0002522]
Value: x bounds the sequence of y iff the upstream-most part of x is upstream of or coincident with the upstream-most part of y, and the downstream-most part of x is downstream of or coincident with the downstream-most part of y

Subject: is bound by sequence of [RO:0002523]
Value: inverse of bounds sequence of

Subject: has subsequence [RO:0002524]
Value: x has subsequence y iff all of the sequence parts of x are sequence parts of y

Subject: is subsequence of [RO:0002525]
Value: inverse of has subsequence

Subject: overlaps sequence of [RO:0002526]
Value: x overlaps the sequence of x if and only if x has a subsequence z and z is a subsequence of y.

Subject: does not overlap sequence of [RO:0002527]
Value: x does not overlaps the sequence of x if and only if there is no z such that x has a subsequence z and z is a subsequence of y.

Subject: is upstream of sequence of [RO:0002528]
Value: inverse of downstream of sequence of

Subject: is downstream of sequence of [RO:0002529]
Value: x is downstream of the sequence of y iff either (1) x and y have sequence units, and all units of x are downstream of all units of y, or (2) x and y are sequence units, and x is either immediately downstream of y, or transitively downstream of y.

Subject: is immediately downstream of sequence of [RO:0002530]
Value: x is immediately downstream of the sequence of y iff either (1) x and y have sequence units, and all units of x are downstream of all units of y, and x is sequentially adjacent to y, or (2) x and y are sequence units, in which case the immediately downstream relation is primitive and defined by context: for DNA bases, y would be adjacent and 5' to y

Subject: is immediately upstream of sequence of [RO:0002531]
Value: inverse of immediately downstream of

Subject: results in ending of [RO:0002552]
Value: p results in the end of s if p results in a change of state in s whereby s either ceases to exist, or s becomes functionally impaired or s has its fate committed such that it is put on a path to be degraded.

Subject: hyperparasite of [RO:0002553]
Value: x is a hyperparasite of y iff x is a parasite of a parasite of the target organism y

Subject: hyperparasitized by [RO:0002554]
Value: inverse of hyperparasite of

Subject: has evidence [RO:0002558]
Value: inverse of is evidence for

Subject: has muscle antagonist [RO:0002568]
Value: m1 has_muscle_antagonist m2 iff m1 has_muscle_insertion s, m2 has_muscle_insection s, m1 acts in opposition to m2, and m2 is responsible for returning the structure to its initial position.

Subject: has branching part [RO:0002569]
Value: inverse of branching part of

Subject: conduit for [RO:0002570]
Value: x is a conduit for y iff y overlaps through the lumen_of of x, and y has parts on either side of the lumen of x.

Subject: lumen of [RO:0002571]
Value: x lumen_of y iff x is the space or substance that is part of y and does not cross any of the inner membranes or boundaries of y that is maximal with respect to the volume of the convex hull.

Subject: luminal space of [RO:0002572]
Value: s is luminal space of x iff s is lumen_of x and s is an immaterial entity

Subject: is direct form of [RO:0002575]
Value: relation p is the direct form of relation q iff p is a subPropertyOf q, p does not have the Transitive characteristic, q does have the Transitive characteristic, and for all x, y: x q y -> exists z1, z2, ..., zn such that x p z1 ... z2n y

Subject: skeleton of [RO:0002576]
Value: inverse of has skeleton

Subject: is indirect form of [RO:0002579]
Value: relation p is the indirect form of relation q iff p is a subPropertyOf q, and there exists some p' such that p' is the direct form of q, p' o p' -> p, and forall x,y : x q y -> either (1) x p y or (2) x p' y

Subject: existence starts at point [RO:0002583]
Value: x existence starts at point y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: has part structure that is capable of [RO:0002584]
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: results in breakdown of [RO:0002586]
Value: p results in breakdown of c if and only if the execution of p leads to c no longer being present at the end of p

Subject: results in catabolism of [RO:0002589]
Value: p results in catabolism of c if and only if p is a catabolic process, and the execution of p results in c being broken into smaller parts with energy being released.

Subject: results in organization of [RO:0002592]
Value: p results in organization of c iff p results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of c

Subject: existence ends at point [RO:0002593]
Value: x existence starts at point y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: is approximately equivalent to [RO:0002603]
Value: x is approximately equivalent to y if it is the case that x is equivalent, identical or near-equivalent to y

Subject: is opposite of [RO:0002604]
Value: x is the opposite of y if there exists some distance metric M, and there exists no z such as M(x,z) <= M(x,y) or M(y,z) <= M(y,x).

Subject: is indistinguishable from [RO:0002605]
Value: x is indistinguishable from y if there exists some distance metric M, and there exists no z such as M(x,z) <= M(x,y) or M(y,z) <= M(y,x).

Subject: is substance that treats [RO:0002606]
Value: c is a substance that treats d if c is a material entity (such as a small molecule or compound) and d is a pathological process, phenotype or disease, and c is capable of some activity that negative regulates or decreases the magnitude of d.

Subject: is marker for [RO:0002607]
Value: c is marker for d iff the presence or occurrence of d is correlated with the presence of occurrence of c, and the observation of c is used to infer the presence or occurrence of d. Note that this does not imply that c and d are in a direct causal relationship, as it may be the case that there is a third entity e that stands in a direct causal relationship with c and d.

Subject: is representative IRI for equivalence set [RO:0002617]
Value: this property relates an IRI to the xsd boolean value \"True\" if the IRI is intended to be the representative IRI for a collection of classes that are mutually equivalent.

Subject: has ectoparasite [RO:0002633]
Value: inverse of ectoparasite of

Subject: has mesoparasite [RO:0002637]
Value: inverse of mesoparasite of

Subject: has intercellular endoparasite [RO:0002639]
Value: inverse of intercellular endoparasite of

Subject: has intracellular endoparasite [RO:0002641]
Value: inverse of intracellular endoparasite of

Subject: produces [RO:0003000]
Value: a produces b if some process that occurs_in a has_output b, where a and b are material entities. Examples: hybridoma cell line produces monoclonal antibody reagent; chondroblast produces avascular GAG-rich matrix.

Subject: produced by [RO:0003001]
Value: a produced_by b iff some process that occurs_in b has_output a.

Subject: has primary input or output [RO:0004007]
Value: p 'has primary input ot output' c iff either (a) p 'has primary input' c or (b) p 'has primary output' c.

Subject: has primary output [RO:0004008]
Value: p has primary output c if (a) p has output c and (b) the goal of process is to modify, produce, or transform c.

Subject: has primary input [RO:0004009]
Value: p has primary input c if (a) p has input c and (b) the goal of process is to modify, consume, or transform c.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect [RO:0004034]
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect [RO:0004035]
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: has epiphyte [RO:0008502]
Value: inverse of epiphyte of

Subject: kleptoparasitized by [RO:0008504]
Value: inverse of kleptoparasite of

Subject: has substance added [RO:0009001]
Value: \"has substance added\" is a relation existing between a (physical) entity and a substance in which the entity has had the substance added to it at some point in time.@en

Subject: has substance removed [RO:0009002]
Value: \"has substance removed\" is a relation existing between two physical entities in which the first entity has had the second entity (a substance) removed from it at some point in time.@en

Subject: immersed in [RO:0009003]
Value: \"immersed in\" is a relation between a (physical) entity and a fluid substance in which the entity is wholely or substantially surrounded by the substance.@en

Subject: has consumer [RO:0009004]
Value: 'has consumer' is a relation between a material entity and an organism in which the former can normally be digested or otherwise absorbed by the latter without immediate or persistent ill effect.@en

Subject: has primary substance added [RO:0009005]
Value: 'has primary substance added' indicates that an entity has had the given substance added to it in a proportion greater than any other added substance.@en

Subject: realized in response to [RO:0009501]
Value: r 'realized in response to' s iff, r is a realizable (e.g. a plant trait such as responsivity to drought), s is an environmental stimulus (a process), and s directly causes the realization of r.

Subject: is carrier of [RO:0010002]
Value: *b* is carrier of *c* at time *t* if and only if *c* *g-depends on* *b* at *t*

Subject: has anatomical participant [RO:0040036]
Value: p has anatomical participant c iff p has participant c, and c is an anatomical entity

Subject: in pro-orthology relationship with [RO:HOM0000025]
Value: 1:many orthology that involves a gene in species A and one of its ortholog in species B, when duplications more recent than the species split have occurred in species B but not in species A.

Subject: in semi-orthology relationship with [RO:HOM0000026]
Value: 1:many orthology that involves a gene in species A and its ortholog in species B, when duplications more recent than the species split have occurred in species A but not in species B.
